Requirement Description

Figure3alandscapesignature/DNATCGAThe immune landscape in Figure 3a includes the expression of immune checkpoints, enrichment of immune signatures, estimation of immune/stromal scores, and quantification of methylated lymphocytes (Teacher Da Yu Hai Tang is really a master of heatmaps!)

https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.05.30.446369v1

Clinical and Translational Medicinehttps://doi.org/10.1002/ctm2.601

FIGURE 3 Differential immune profile across MIBC subtypes and its association with genomic alteration and immunotherapeutic response. (A) Heatmap showing the immune profile in the MIBC-TCGA cohort, with the top panel showing the expression of genes involved in immune checkpoint targets and the bottom panel showing the enrichment level of 24 microenvironment cell types. The immune enrichment score, stromal enrichment score and DNA methylation of tumour-infiltrating lymphocytes (MeTILs) were annotated at the top of the heatmap.

Application Scenarios

RMOVICSkey figureMOVICS

Da Yu Hai Tang wrote a magical R package called MOVICS. By running your own data through it, you can reproduce the key figures from the paper. How do we organize these figures to tell a story? This article is a great example of applying MOVICS.

DNA methylation of tumour-infiltrating lymphocyte (MeTIL)

Calculate the DNA methylation score of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (MeTIL) based on methylation data, and create heatmaps based on immune checkpoint expression and tumor immune microenvironment enrichment.

#  # Load custom functions
standarize.fun <- function(indata=NULL, halfwidth=NULL, centerFlag=T, scaleFlag=T) {  
  outdata=t(scale(t(indata), center=centerFlag, scale=scaleFlag))
  if (!is.null(halfwidth)) {
    outdata[outdata>halfwidth]=halfwidth
    outdata[outdata<(-halfwidth)]= -halfwidth
  }
  return(outdata)
}

Start Drawing

complexheatmappheatmapUse pheatmap in complexheatmap to draw three heatmaps separately, then combine them.

# Set colors
clust.col <- c("#DD492E","#40548A","#32A087","#EC7D21")
heatmap.BlBkRd <- c("#54FEFF","#32ABAA","#125456","#000000","#510000","#A20000","#F30000")
blue <- "#5bc0eb"
gold <- "#ECE700"
cyan <- "#00B3D0"

annCol.tcga$ImmuneScore <- as.numeric(est.tcga[rownames(annCol.tcga),"ImmuneScore"])
annCol.tcga$StromalScore <- as.numeric(est.tcga[rownames(annCol.tcga),"StromalScore"])
annCol.tcga <- annCol.tcga[order(annCol.tcga$CMOIC),]
annColors.tcga <- list() #  # Construct the legend color of the heat map
annColors.tcga[["CMOIC"]] <- c("CS1" = clust.col[1],
                               "CS2" = clust.col[2],
                               "CS3" = clust.col[3],
                               "CS4" = clust.col[4])
annColors.tcga[["ImmuneScore"]] <- inferno(64)
annColors.tcga[["StromalScore"]] <- viridis(64)

## 1 Heat map 1: immune checkpoint gene expression
indata <- log2(tpm[intersect(rownames(tpm),imm.targets),] + 1)
hm1 <- pheatmap(standarize.fun(indata[imm.targets,rownames(annCol.tcga)],halfwidth = 2), #  # Normalize expression profile data
                border_color = NA, #  # No borders around heatmap cells
                annotation_col = annCol.tcga[,c("CMOIC","StromalScore","ImmuneScore")],
                annotation_colors = annColors.tcga[c("CMOIC","StromalScore","ImmuneScore")],
                color = colorpanel(64,low=blue,mid = "black",high=gold),
                show_rownames = T, #  # Show row names
                show_colnames = F, #  # Do not show column names
                cellheight = 12, #  # Fixed heatmap height
                cellwidth = 0.6, #  # Fixed heatmap width
                name = "ICI", #  # Legend name
                cluster_rows = F, #  # No clustering for rows
                cluster_cols = F) #  # No clustering for columns

#pdf("CheckPoint_heatmap.pdf",width = 10,height = 10)
hm1

#dev.off()

## 2 Heatmap 2: Tumor Immune Microenvironment Enrichment Scores
hm2 <- pheatmap(standarize.fun(tcga.immune.gsva[immune.sig.ccr.order,rownames(annCol.tcga)],halfwidth = 1), # 
                border_color = NA,
                color = NMF:::ccRamp(x = heatmap.BlBkRd,n = 64),
                gaps_row = c(14,22), #  # Segmentation by immune cell class
                show_rownames = T,
                show_colnames = F,
                cellheight = 12,
                cellwidth = 0.6,
                name = "TIME",
                cluster_rows = F,
                cluster_cols = F)

#pdf("TIMEheatmap.pdf",width = 10,height = 10)
hm2

#dev.off()

## 3MeTIL MeTIL score
hm3 <- pheatmap(standarize.fun(t(annCol.tcga[,"MeTIL",drop = F]),halfwidth = 1),
                border_color = NA,
                color = NMF:::ccRamp(c(cyan,"black","#F12AFE"),64),
                show_rownames = T,
                show_colnames = F,
                cellheight = 12,
                cellwidth = 0.6,
                name = "MeTIL",
                cluster_rows = F,
                cluster_cols = F)

hm3

pdfIllustratorYou can use the following method to combine the three images into a single image. You can also export the three images separately to PDF files, then open them in software like Illustrator and combine them.

#  # Merge the heatmap and export
pdf("TIME.pdf",width = 10,height = 10)
draw(hm1 %v% hm2 %v% hm3, 
     heatmap_legend_side = "right", 
     annotation_legend_side = "right")
